Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "PFX Certificates not accepted" (#7342) at NuGet/NuGetGallery
Events.RelatedBody:
### Describe the bug
I have a DigiCert signing certificate, which is a PFX.  I exported it to a .cer so I would have both.  When I build a package in Visual Studio 2019, I must provide a PFX file to sign it.  That works fine.  However, I can only upload a .cer to NuGet as my certificate.  NuGet does not match the PFX-signed package to the .cer file.  

### Expected behavior
I would expect NuGet to accept my .cer or my .pfx certificates.

Events.RelatedBody:
## Details about Problem

* VS Version: Master\29114.15 preview branch
* NuGet Version: Implicit NuGet Client Release-5.2.x\5.2.0.6090
* OS Version: Windows-10- 17763.RS5_Release.180914-1434.

## Installation steps: 
Install VS from: [https://devdiv.visualstudio.com/DevDiv/_build/results?buildId=2850307&view=results]

## Repro steps: 
1. Create a new Class Library (.NET Framework) App named Lib1.
2. Add a new Class Library (.NET Framework) project to the solution Lib1 named Lib2.
3. Open project Lib1 PM UI and install a Nunit package with Package Reference format.
4. Open project Lib2 PM UI and install a Nunit package with Package Reference format **(Dont close the project Lib1 PM UI)**.
5. Unload the project Lib2 and edit csproj file.
6. Set MSBuild property RestorePackagesWithLockFile to true in csproj file.
  `  <RestorePackagesWithLockFile>true</RestorePackagesWithLockFile>`
7. Reload the project Lib2.
8. Open project Lib2 PM UI by clicking Manage NuGet Packages.

## Expected:
The project Lib2 PM UI can be opened.

## Actual:
There is no responding when clicking Manage NuGet Packages of the project Lib2.

## Notes:
1.The issue not repro when adding two project packages with PackageReference format from solution PM UI together.
2. The issue also repro on VS Master\29114.15 + NuGet Client Dev\5.3.0.6098.

Events.RelatedBody:
From this issue: https://github.com/NuGetPackageExplorer/NuGetPackageExplorer/issues/722

If you have a nuspec with an empty `frameworkReference` element in a framework reference group, the parsing succeeds despite this being invalid. This causes an error later during a lazy LINQ enumeration. 

The parsing logic for the manifest should throw eagerly in this case.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "Restoring PackageReferences by passes Xamarin.Mac networking stack" (#8330) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
## Details about Problem

NuGet product used: VS Mac

NuGet version: 5.2

VS version:

OS version: macOS 10.13

Worked before? If so, with which NuGet version: N/A

## Detailed repro steps so we can see the same problem

1. Run a restore on a project that uses PackageReferences or install/update a NuGet package that uses PackageReferences
2. NuGet bypasses the native Xamarin.Mac networking stack.

VS Mac has a custom HttpHandlerResourceProvider which ensures the Xamarin.Mac's NSUrlSessionHandler (HttpMessageHandler) is used when HttpClient requests are made using the SourceRepository.

Certain operations that involve PackageReferences do not use the provided SourceRepository instances which then causes NuGet to use Mono's networking stack to make HttpClient requests.

The problem seems to be the CachingSourceProvider creates its own set of INuGetResourceProvider's

    _resourceProviders.AddRange(Repository.Provider.GetCoreV3());

https://github.com/NuGet/NuGet.Client/blob/423aec56fa69a5633c1a33a143a8a0a75cd2b5cd/src/NuGet.Core/NuGet.Protocol/CachingSourceProvider.cs#L31-L36

Which bypasses the custom HttpHandlerResourceProvider that VS Mac uses.

NuGet needs a way to allow for the CachingSourceProvider to use VS Mac's custom HttpHandlerResourceProvider.
